  "text": "We chose to use focus groups and included men and women of various ages to encourage a diverse set of perspectives [31] . Participants were shown images of a familiar food and were asked to choose the portion they would ideally consume for lunch. They were then shown an image that was 25% smaller and were asked to imagine consuming this portion instead. A 25% reduction in portion size was selected based on the study of Rolls and colleagues [CITATION_1] . An advantage of our approach was that a visual demonstration of the reduction in portion size was included before participants were asked to reflect on how they would feel if they were to eat this smaller portion for lunch. Participants were told that the new portion was 25% smaller than their original portion. This reference to percentage reduction was specified to ensure the manipulation was standardized across participants.",
